node.title: DMTV Milkshake: Soft Geometry on Finding the Give in Minimalism

node.text: For this week’s Milkshake, we spoke to @bimmawilliams, co-founder and host of the @claimastories podcast. Claima — ”claima” as in “claim a seat at the table” — is a podcast with a mission: to give young BIPOC creatives the inspiration, and roadmap, they need to make good on their ambitions. Bimma joins us from the road — specifically from, a custom-rigged 1993 Mitsubishi Delica Starwagon rechristened as “Storytella,” his mobile podcast studio during a 30-day, four-city tour of the West Coast. Here, he gives his best advice for young BIPOC creatives looking for professional advancement and shares a few of the stories that have moved him most. \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

node.title: DMTV Milkshake: Making Space for BIPOC Creatives

🔄 Rotate Your Device 🔄
Inside the Dallas studio of sculptor Dan Lam (@sopopomo), burbling, bubbling and bright works of art appear to move on their own. Commissioned by @Genesis_usa, the artist transformed her distinct style into her first-ever digital art car and NFT inspired by her time in the G70. Lam took inspiration from her time driving the G70, and worked with digital designer Stephen Judge (@stephenthejudge) to bring her vision of the world passing outside the windows to life. #G70artcars #GenesisG70 #G70 #artcars #digitalartcars #NFTs #BorntoMove

node.title: Sculptor Dan Lam Blends the Outside World into Her Genesis G70 Art Car

node.text: For this week’s Milkshake, we invited @noznozawa, founder of San Francisco’s Noz Design. Tune in for Noz’s take on how to create a home you love (while putting to the side, at least for the moment, the resale value) — plus her favorite color combinations, post-pandemic home design, and the difference between “Asian Art” and “Modern Architecture from 1940 to 1945”. Featuring a vessel from @angusandceleste! \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

node.text: @kalonstudios, a brand known for their dedication to sustainability, has released their first collection in over a year: Highland. Generous in scale, the solid oak furniture pieces – dining table, chair, bench and desk – look to the Brutalist qualities of cantilevered forms and imperfect curves for proportional balance. The occasional knobby detail calls attention to oak trees in northern California, which is where Highland gets its name. \\\ Read more about the Highland Collection at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: Picturing yourself somewhere along the Mediterranean? Allow @oiside_outdoor to improve upon that vision with a more up-to-date and efficient lounge chair. Gandula is made using harder-wearing materials and fast-drying fabric for an improved design that maintains the essence of the traditional furniture design. Available in individual and double versions, the foldable chairs can be fixed in four different positions that lock to prevent the frame from suddenly slamming shut. \\\ Read more about Gandula at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: @levichristiansen’s Shapes From Home furniture collection is quite literally the stuff of dreams – the five pieces were inspired by lucid dreams of a world of objects buried within his subconscious mind. The dreams first showed up when Christiansen was a child, only coming to fruition after his mother met an oracle who told her that his work is reminiscent of another life. Inspired, he dove into a place he’s never seen in waking life to make his visions real. \\\ Read more about the surreal experience that brought Shapes From Home to life and learn about the collection at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: Designed by Sangmin Oh, a 4th year student at Design Academy Eindhoven and founder of @osangmin_studio, Thankspressure is a tapestry project that prompts the user to engage in acupressure through dance in order to treat common ailments. Raised pebble-like features throughout the rug map out various dance steps that Oh believes will help relieve headaches, eye strain, stiffness, and more. The rug, produced in collaboration with @textielmuseum, combines eastern acupressure with western sports dances on a colorful stage. (And don't worry: there's an instruction manual.) \\\ Read more about Thankspressure at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: For this week’s Milkshake, we’re talking to Utharaa Zacharias and Palaash Chaudhary, co-founders of the @soft.geometry design studio. Here, we talk to the designers — who base their practice between San Jose, California, and Kochi, India — about finding that titular softness in minimalism, the most precious object in their workshop, and the relationship between craftwork and modern aesthetics. \\\ #dmtvmilkshake #designmilktv

Los Angeles’ rampant housing crisis is complicated but one of the most obvious issues is low inventory. Thanks to the city’s Small Lot Subdivision Ordinance, single-family homes can now be replaced with smaller, more affordable multi-family residences that help increase neighborhood density while keeping in line with the scale and character of the surrounding homes. One such project is Canyon Homes, a boutique communion of five residences located just west of Los Feliz at the base of the Hollywood Hills. The mini neighborhood was designed by Lorcan O’Herlihy Architects (@loharchitects) with stunning interiors by @discinteriors, in collaboration with @theplatformexperiment and @lawsonfenning. \\\ Read more about Canyon Homes at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: According to research done by U.K. cybersecurity company Zobi, 30% of all smart home devices are hacked, with 1.8 billion passwords readily available over the dark web. Online privacy is becoming a highly prevalent issue with the proliferation of vulnerable smart home devices, so it makes sense that an entirely new category of devices have emerged to designed not only to protect you from digital harm, but to alert you if you're ever under threat. London-based design studio Blond’s smart-home device, Hedgehog, is designed to autonomously defend against cyber-attacks on your WiFi while looking just as cute as its namesake. \\\ Read more about Hedgehog at the link in bio. 🔗

node.text: Plant lovers, this one is for you. @afterarchitecture’s new Grow on Me tables integrate your beloved houseplants into your everyday living. To house your greenery, planters are nestled into each of the cylindrical table legs which then support square tabletops that can pivot to create non-traditional seating layouts. \\\ At the link in bio, read more about After Architecture's design and the myriad ways to utilize Grow on Me tables in your space.

node.text: Yuri Suzuki devised Sonic Bloom to capture three audible themes; people, nature and the surrounding environment - and blend them into an exploration of universal communication. Sonic Bloom seeks to facilitate human interactions in spaces where they don't usually occur through an installation that invites people to go outside and reconnect with the environment, bringing the city’s community closer together through a sense of shared experience in time, place and space. Sonic Bloom is on view in Brown Hart Gardens, London through August 23rd, 2022. Learn more @mayfair_ldn.

Designed by French-Brazilian architects Triptyque Architecture, the
Villa M aims to create a new pact between city, nature, and health. The building houses a dynamic healthcare center and boasts a living facade conceived to house medicinal herbal plants, fruit trees and perennial species. “The edifice
itself is the support for this vertical garden, which will grow and occupy the entire façade, turning the building into a vertical, medicinal forest and becoming the main architecture”, says Triptyque partner, Guillaume Sibaud. \\\ Learn more @triptyquearchitecture.
